'''Nutrient profiling''', also '''nutritional profiling''', is the science of classifying or ranking foods by their nutritional composition in order to promote health and prevent disease.<ref>[http://www.who.int/nutrition/publications/profiling/WHO_IASO_report2010.pdf?ua=1 Nutrient Profiling: Report of a WHO/IASO Technical Meeting, London, United Kingdom, 4-6 October 2010, accessed 10/15/2014.]</ref><ref name="who">{{cite web | url=http://www.who.int/nutrition/topics/profiling/en/ | title=Nutrient Profiling | publisher=World Health Organization (WHO) | accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid=20515553 | title=Nutritional profiles in a public health perspective: a critical review | vauthors=Foltran F, Verduci E, Ghidina M, Campoy C, Jany KD, Widhalm K, Biasucci G, Vögele C, Halpern GM, Gregori D | journal=Journal of International Medical Research | year=2010 | volume=38 | pages=318–85 | doi=10.1177/147323001003800202}}</ref> A common use of nutrient profiling is in the creation of [[nutritional rating systems]] to help consumers identify nutritious food.<ref name="who"/><ref name="cphn-uofw">{{cite web | url=http://depts.washington.edu/uwcphn/work/fdenv/nutrprofiling.shtml | title=Nutrient Profiling | publisher=Center for Public Health Nutrition (University of Washington) | accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref>
