[[File:Starburst in a Dwarf Irregular Galaxy.jpg|thumb|Starburst in [[NGC 1569]] a Dwarf Irregular Galaxy ([[NASA]] photo).]]
A '''starburst''' is an astrophysical process that involves [[star formation]] occurring at a rate that is large compared to the rate that is typically observed. This starburst activity will consume the available interstellar gas supply over a timespan that is much shorter than the lifetime of the galaxy. For example, the nebula [[NGC 6334]] has a star formation rate estimated to be 3600 [[Solar Mass]]es per million years<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.physastro.iastate.edu/research/highlights/ngc-6334-mini-starburst-region|title=NGC 6334 – A Mini Starburst Region {{!}} Department of Physics & Astronomy|website=www.physastro.iastate.edu|access-date=2016-10-10}}</ref> compared the star formation rate of the entire [[Milky Way]] of about seven million [[solar mass]]es per million years.<ref>{{cite journal|first2=Barbara|last2=Whitney|title=The present-day star formation rate of the Milky-Way determined from Spitzer detected young stellar objects|date=2010|last1=Robitaille|first1=Thomas|arxiv=1001.3672|doi=10.1088/2041-8205/710/1/L11|volume=710|issue=1|journal=The Astrophysical Journal|pages=L11–L15|bibcode = 2010ApJ...710L..11R }}</ref> Due to the high amount of star formation a starburst is usually accompanied by much higher gas pressure and a larger ratio of [[Hydrogen cyanide]] to [[Carbon monoxide]] [[Emission-line]]<nowiki/>s than are usually observed.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=Galaxies in the Universe|last2=Gallagher III|first2=John|date=2007|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|isbn=978-0-521-67186-6|location=New York|page=289|last1=Sparke|first1=Linda|authorlink2=John Gallagher III}}</ref> 
[[File:30 Doradus, Tarantula Nebula.jpg|thumb|[[Tarantula Nebula]], the largest starburst region in the local group.]]
Starburst can occur in entire galaxies or just regions of space. A starburst region is a region of space that is undergoing a large amount of star formation. For example, the [[Tarantula Nebula]] is a [[Nebula]] in the [[Large Magellanic Cloud]] which has one of the highest star formation rates in the [[Local Group]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lebouteiller|first=V.|last2=Bernard-Salas|first2=J.|last3=Brandl|first3=B.|last4=Whelan|first4=D. G.|last5=Wu|first5=Y.|last6=Charmandaris|first6=V.|last7=Devost|first7=D.|last8=Houck|first8=J. R.|date=2008-06-10|title=Chemical composition and mixing in giant HII regions: NGC3603, 30Doradus, and N66|journal=The Astrophysical Journal|volume=680|issue=1|pages=398–419|doi=10.1086/587503|issn=0004-637X|bibcode=2008ApJ...680..398L|arxiv = 0710.4549 }}</ref> By contrast a starburst galaxy is an entire galaxy that is experiencing a very high star formation rate. One notable example being [[Messier 82]] in which the gas pressure is 100 times greater than in the local neighborhood and it is forming stars at about the same rate as the [[Milky Way]] in a region about 600 parsecs across.<ref name=":0" /> At this rate M82 will consume its 200 million [[Solar Mass]]es of atomic and molecular hydrogen in 100 Mega years (its [[Free-fall time]]).<ref name=":0" />

Starburst regions can occur in different shapes, for example in [[Messier 94]] the inner ring is a star burst region.<ref>{{cite journal|date=2004|title=The Inner Ring of NGC 4736: Star Formation on a Resonant Pattern|journal=[[Astronomical Journal]]|volume=127|issue=1|pages=58–74|bibcode=2004AJ....127...58M|doi=10.1086/380610|author=C. Muñoz-Tuñón|author2=N. Caon|author3=J. Aguerri|author4=L. Alfonso}}</ref> [[Messier 82]] has a starburst core of about 600 parsec in diameter.<ref name=":0" /> Starbursts are common during galaxy mergers such as the [[Antennae Galaxies]]. In the case of mergers the starburst can either be local or galaxy wide depending on the galaxies and how they are merging.

